1537
00:50:14,392 --> 00:50:16,352
- I forgot. - You forgot, right?

1538
00:50:16,492 --> 00:50:17,592
We have to...

1539
00:50:17,862 --> 00:50:19,021
- play the games here. - Yes.

1540
00:50:19,022 --> 00:50:20,692
We need to have coffee before that.

1541
00:50:20,792 --> 00:50:23,162
- But we can't be too relaxed. - Right.

1542
00:50:24,532 --> 00:50:25,532
Wait.

1543
00:50:25,632 --> 00:50:26,971
When were you born, Som?

1544
00:50:26,972 --> 00:50:28,101
I was born in 1990.

1545
00:50:28,102 --> 00:50:29,831
- I see. - In 1990.

1546
00:50:29,832 --> 00:50:31,772
You're the only one who was born in the 90s.

1547
00:50:32,202 --> 00:50:34,042
- How old are you, then? - I'm 39.

1548
00:50:34,712 --> 00:50:35,941
- You're 39? - Yes.

1549
00:50:35,942 --> 00:50:37,642
- So, you were born in 1988? - Yes.

1550
00:50:38,112 --> 00:50:39,241
When were you born?

1551
00:50:39,242 --> 00:50:41,212
- In 1972. - In 1972.

1552
00:50:41,352 --> 00:50:43,052
- We share the same zodiac sign. - We do!

1553
00:50:43,212 --> 00:50:44,252
- Yes. - I see.

1554
00:50:44,482 --> 00:50:45,551
We were all born in the Year of the Mouse.

1555
00:50:45,552 --> 00:50:47,551
I'm as old as this restaurant.

1556
00:50:47,552 --> 00:50:49,492
(He's a year older, actually.)

1557
00:50:50,822 --> 00:50:52,662
- You're right. - And Children's Grand Park.

1558
00:50:53,062 --> 00:50:55,292
Children's Grand Park. We're all similar.

1559
00:50:55,562 --> 00:50:57,362
The snack bar, Children's Grand Park, and me.

1560
00:50:57,432 --> 00:50:59,162
This snack bar, Children's Grand Park...

1561
00:51:00,202 --> 00:51:02,001
(Focusing on the noodles again)

1562
00:51:02,002 --> 00:51:03,742
- You practically grew up together. - Yes.

1563
00:51:04,402 --> 00:51:06,701
That's why it suits his taste.

1564
00:51:06,702 --> 00:51:07,771
It totally does.

1565
00:51:07,772 --> 00:51:09,572
(The chemistry between those of the same age)

1566
00:51:10,342 --> 00:51:11,812
That was a great meal.

1567
00:51:12,012 --> 00:51:13,112
I'm full.

1568
00:51:13,852 --> 00:51:15,851
- We have to decide who pays. - Good.

1569
00:51:15,852 --> 00:51:17,322
Without letting the owner know,

1570
00:51:17,622 --> 00:51:19,951
we'll take out one of our belongings.

1571
00:51:19,952 --> 00:51:21,592
- That's retro. - It is.

1572
00:51:21,692 --> 00:51:23,121
- That's from blind dates. - Yes.

1573
00:51:23,122 --> 00:51:25,191
It feels like I'm back in 2003.

1574
00:51:25,192 --> 00:51:26,961
- How do you think? Isn't it nice? - It's very retro.

1575
00:51:26,962 --> 00:51:29,361
- You and this place... - We're a good match, right?

1576
00:51:29,362 --> 00:51:31,361
- Yes. - They clearly grew up together.

1577
00:51:31,362 --> 00:51:32,601
(They certainly have something in common.)

1578
00:51:32,602 --> 00:51:35,301
So, we show her five of our belongings,

1579
00:51:35,302 --> 00:51:37,801
and she gets to rule them out 1 by 1.

1580
00:51:37,802 --> 00:51:39,771
- All right. - The last one remaining will be...

1581
00:51:39,772 --> 00:51:41,471
- The last one. - Yes, the last one.

1582
00:51:41,472 --> 00:51:43,342
- The owner of the last item pays. - Yes.

1583
00:51:43,542 --> 00:51:44,581
Okay.

1584
00:51:44,582 --> 00:51:46,311
- Get your items out. - Okay.

1585
00:51:46,312 --> 00:51:48,681
The owner isn't watching,

1586
00:51:48,682 --> 00:51:50,182
so we'll...

1587
00:51:50,552 --> 00:51:51,722
Wait.

1588
00:51:51,952 --> 00:51:54,392
- It can be literally anything? - Anything.

1589
00:51:55,392 --> 00:51:57,992
(They must be chosen by the owner.)

1590
00:51:58,662 --> 00:52:00,362
(A mysterious smile)

1591
00:52:00,762 --> 00:52:01,891
(They all submitted their items.)

1592
00:52:01,892 --> 00:52:03,261
(Wet tissue, paper crane, elephant, cotton swab, and lip balm)

1593
00:52:03,262 --> 00:52:05,302
You can take them out 1 by 1...

1594
00:52:05,332 --> 00:52:06,761
and leave just one.

1595
00:52:06,762 --> 00:52:08,231
You pass if she takes yours out.

1596
00:52:08,232 --> 00:52:09,672
- Yes. - You want to be chosen.

1597
00:52:10,972 --> 00:52:12,372
Take them out 1 by 1, ma'am.

1598
00:52:13,602 --> 00:52:15,011
- That one? - Oh, my gosh.

1599
00:52:15,012 --> 00:52:16,112
Okay.

1600
00:52:16,372 --> 00:52:17,582
Yes.

1601
00:52:18,742 --> 00:52:19,842
Oh, yes.

1602
00:52:20,652 --> 00:52:22,211
(Lastly, )

1603
00:52:22,212 --> 00:52:26,182
(it's the paper crane versus the cotton swab.)

1604
00:52:29,192 --> 00:52:30,322
A cotton swab.

1605
00:52:30,662 --> 00:52:33,261
- But the cotton swab was... - The cotton swab!

1606
00:52:33,262 --> 00:52:35,092
- so half-hearted. - Whose is this?

1607
00:52:35,962 --> 00:52:37,332
- Som. - Hey, Som.

1608
00:52:37,402 --> 00:52:38,461
- Why... - This is your day.

1609
00:52:38,462 --> 00:52:39,832
- Hey. - A cotton swab?

1610
00:52:40,362 --> 00:52:42,601
- Today... - Even I wouldn't pick that.

1611
00:52:42,602 --> 00:52:44,172
- This is her day. - That's incredible.

1612
00:52:44,202 --> 00:52:45,301
Som.

1613
00:52:45,302 --> 00:52:46,401
- Thanks for the food. - Thanks for paying.

1614
00:52:46,402 --> 00:52:47,641
- Thanks for paying. - Thanks.

1615
00:52:47,642 --> 00:52:49,741
- Goodness. - She's...

1616
00:52:49,742 --> 00:52:51,042
She's doing all of it.

1617
00:52:51,082 --> 00:52:53,642
When would I get a chance to buy you food?

1618
00:52:53,882 --> 00:52:55,882
Why? Is this the last day we're seeing each other?

1619
00:52:56,552 --> 00:52:58,281
Should we get a cup of coffee quickly?

1620
00:52:58,282 --> 00:52:59,852
- Yes. - Sure.

1621
00:53:00,522 --> 00:53:03,121
- Thanks for the food, Som. - Sure.

1622
00:53:03,122 --> 00:53:04,221
- Thank you. - Thank you.

1623
00:53:04,222 --> 00:53:05,461
Do I also have to buy coffee?

1624
00:53:05,462 --> 00:53:06,761
- No. - No.

1625
00:53:06,762 --> 00:53:08,031
- No, right? - Are we playing one more game?

1626
00:53:08,032 --> 00:53:10,261
- We'll do it once we're there. - Yes, over there.

1627
00:53:10,262 --> 00:53:11,861
- We'll see you soon, ma'am. - Okay.

1628
00:53:11,862 --> 00:53:13,362
- We'll be back. - See you soon!

1629
00:53:13,802 --> 00:53:16,231
Knowing where we're going next...

1630
00:53:16,232 --> 00:53:17,441
makes me feel so at ease.

1631
00:53:17,442 --> 00:53:19,342
- You don't have to find it. - Right.

1632
00:53:19,672 --> 00:53:21,411
It's so interesting. I was startled earlier.

1633
00:53:21,412 --> 00:53:22,512
Totally.

1634
00:53:22,542 --> 00:53:24,481
- We got lucky. - You know,

1635
00:53:24,482 --> 00:53:27,381
those two have been working in the same place...

1636
00:53:27,382 --> 00:53:29,181
and running the place...

1637
00:53:29,182 --> 00:53:30,722
for over 50 years.

1638
00:53:31,352 --> 00:53:32,452
And if we fail...

1639
00:53:34,852 --> 00:53:36,992
- I'd feel so bad. - I could never go back to school.

1640
00:53:37,422 --> 00:53:39,391
- I... - I'd feel terrible.

1641
00:53:39,392 --> 00:53:41,762
I have to keep coming here. What do I do?

1642
00:53:41,962 --> 00:53:43,261
- Well... - I'd have to take a detour.

1643
00:53:43,262 --> 00:53:44,262
I'd feel terrible.

1644
00:53:44,263 --> 00:53:46,301
I have to go all the way to the main gate, then.

1645
00:53:46,302 --> 00:53:48,801
- "Keep Out, Yoo Yeon Seok." - No!

1646
00:53:48,802 --> 00:53:50,001
- No! - "Keep Out."

1647
00:53:50,002 --> 00:53:51,178
("Keep Out, Yoo Yeon Seok from Whenever Possible")

1648
00:53:51,202 --> 00:53:52,402
This must be it.

1649
00:53:52,572 --> 00:53:53,771
It says, "Coffee."

1650
00:53:53,772 --> 00:53:54,942
Coffee's on me.

1651
00:53:55,212 --> 00:53:56,571
- Really? - Come on.

1652
00:53:56,572 --> 00:53:57,742
Is it on Professor Ahn?

1653
00:53:59,412 --> 00:54:00,481
- Come on. - Professor Ahn.

1654
00:54:00,482 --> 00:54:01,911
- We're in Sejong University, so... - Sure.

1655
00:54:01,912 --> 00:54:03,798
- Thank you, professor. - Pay this for us, Professor Ahn.

1656
00:54:03,822 --> 00:54:05,551
- All of them to go? - Yes.

1657
00:54:05,552 --> 00:54:07,951
(The professor takes out his credit card.)

1658
00:54:07,952 --> 00:54:09,322
Thank you.

1659
00:54:09,692 --> 00:54:12,192
- Professor Ahn bought us coffee. - All of it is...

1660
00:54:12,392 --> 00:54:13,861
(Som went to the bathroom.)

1661
00:54:13,862 --> 00:54:14,962
For some reason,

1662
00:54:15,232 --> 00:54:17,862
I'm all excited, although it's not even my graduation.

1663
00:54:18,302 --> 00:54:19,631
- Right. - The weather's so good.

1664
00:54:19,632 --> 00:54:21,071
- Yes, even the weather is nice. - Yes.

1665
00:54:21,072 --> 00:54:22,531
- It feels like spring. - Indeed.

1666
00:54:22,532 --> 00:54:23,532
(The graduation and entrance season marks the first scent of spring.)

1667
00:54:23,533 --> 00:54:24,641
- It's the most thrilling period. - Yes.

1668
00:54:24,642 --> 00:54:25,942
The first year of college.

1669
00:54:26,002 --> 00:54:28,042
The spring breeze...

1670
00:54:28,112 --> 00:54:29,441
makes you so excited.

1671
00:54:29,442 --> 00:54:30,682
To be frank,

1672
00:54:30,982 --> 00:54:33,241
from a freshman's perspective,

1673
00:54:33,242 --> 00:54:35,851
the ones graduating are huge seniors.

1674
00:54:35,852 --> 00:54:36,981
- Right. - That's true.

1675
00:54:36,982 --> 00:54:39,151
- They look like... - When you think about it,

1676
00:54:39,152 --> 00:54:41,151
given that you never took a break, you could graduate...

1677
00:54:41,152 --> 00:54:42,721
- at 23. - At 23.

1678
00:54:42,722 --> 00:54:45,391
- Like 23 or 24. - They looked like such grown-ups.

1679
00:54:45,392 --> 00:54:47,862
Even a sophomore was like this mature person.

1680
00:54:48,032 --> 00:54:51,132
- The female seniors intimidated me. - Right.

1681
00:54:51,362 --> 00:54:52,961
- Now, they're... - Babies.

1682
00:54:52,962 --> 00:54:55,131
- They're babies! - The babies are...

1683
00:54:55,132 --> 00:54:56,232
Yes.

1684
00:54:56,502 --> 00:54:58,042
We had to be so polite to the seniors.

1685
00:54:58,702 --> 00:55:00,772
- It was worse in your time, right? - It was.

1686
00:55:00,872 --> 00:55:03,272
The ones who were one year ahead of me...

1687
00:55:03,472 --> 00:55:04,811
were like, "Yeah."

1688
00:55:04,812 --> 00:55:05,812
(Chic and arrogant)

1689
00:55:06,842 --> 00:55:08,751
- One year apart. - We were only one year apart.

1690
00:55:08,752 --> 00:55:10,381
They were only a year older.

1691
00:55:10,382 --> 00:55:13,782
In hindsight, they were so conceited.

1692
00:55:14,152 --> 00:55:16,351
- As if they're such mature people. - Yes.

1693
00:55:16,352 --> 00:55:17,661
- They wanted to be taken seriously. - Yes.

1694
00:55:17,662 --> 00:55:19,061
That's what they looked like.

1695
00:55:19,062 --> 00:55:20,421
But now...

1696
00:55:20,422 --> 00:55:21,761
- I feel like I was also like that. - Right?

1697
00:55:21,762 --> 00:55:23,861
- Really? - I mean, to the younger ones.

1698
00:55:23,862 --> 00:55:25,861
- I was like, "Hey." - They do that in college.

1699
00:55:25,862 --> 00:55:27,382
They even end the sentence with "kid."

1700
00:55:28,002 --> 00:55:29,202
- "Hey, kid." - "Hey, kid."

1701
00:55:31,842 --> 00:55:35,211
And the ones returning to school after their military service...

1702
00:55:35,212 --> 00:55:36,272
(Exclaiming)

1703
00:55:36,572 --> 00:55:38,941
You can never look them in the eye.

1704
00:55:38,942 --> 00:55:40,282
- They're elders. - Yes.

1705
00:55:40,482 --> 00:55:42,481
They were sitting in the student lounge like this,

1706
00:55:42,482 --> 00:55:44,198
- and I couldn't go inside. - They're like elders.

1707
00:55:44,222 --> 00:55:45,451
- Elders. - The returning students.

1708
00:55:45,452 --> 00:55:47,251
- After their military service. - Yes.

1709
00:55:47,252 --> 00:55:50,422
Word gets out that a scary one is coming back.

1710
00:55:50,592 --> 00:55:51,861
They were so scary.

1711
00:55:51,862 --> 00:55:53,491
- Thank you for the coffee. - Thanks.

1712
00:55:53,492 --> 00:55:55,231
- Thanks. - Thank you.

1713
00:55:55,232 --> 00:55:56,932
Thanks for the coffee, Professor Ahn.

1714
00:55:57,762 --> 00:55:58,932
It's good.

1715
00:55:59,362 --> 00:56:00,772
- It's on. - It's on.

1716
00:56:01,572 --> 00:56:02,602
Green light.

1717
00:56:04,442 --> 00:56:05,672
This is it, right?

1718
00:56:05,802 --> 00:56:07,972
Yes, our Whenever Guest, Lee Ok Soon.

1719
00:56:08,312 --> 00:56:10,171
- Lee Ok Soon. - Gosh.

1720
00:56:10,172 --> 00:56:12,481
- With 56 years of history... - It's been around since 1973.

1721
00:56:12,482 --> 00:56:13,641
- It says it here. - You're right.

1722
00:56:13,642 --> 00:56:15,152
Goodness. Aren't you...

1723
00:56:15,682 --> 00:56:17,151
Ms. Lee Ok Soon?

1724
00:56:17,152 --> 00:56:18,252
That's me.

1725
00:56:18,452 --> 00:56:20,181
- This is the place. - It is.

1726
00:56:20,182 --> 00:56:22,991
Goodness. That was amazing!

1727
00:56:22,992 --> 00:56:24,361
- It was right on the money. - Indeed.

1728
00:56:24,362 --> 00:56:25,842
- Come inside. - It was made in 1973.

1729
00:56:26,062 --> 00:56:27,502
Nice to meet you for the first time.

1730
00:56:27,592 --> 00:56:28,991
- Gosh. - Hello.

1731
00:56:28,992 --> 00:56:30,331
- It's a pleasure. - Yes.

1732
00:56:30,332 --> 00:56:31,932
- It's nice to meet you, ma'am. - Hi.

1733
00:56:32,362 --> 00:56:33,562
I'm so glad to see you.

1734
00:56:33,832 --> 00:56:36,401
- Set A looks good. - I know, right?

1735
00:56:36,402 --> 00:56:37,842
(Lee Ok Soon, second Whenever Guest)

1736
00:56:38,102 --> 00:56:39,902
- Thank you. - Rice cake?

1737
00:56:40,072 --> 00:56:41,472
- My gosh. - No way.

1738
00:56:42,042 --> 00:56:44,041
- It feels like... - It's rainbow-colored.

1739
00:56:44,042 --> 00:56:45,942
We're at the house of a friend's mom.

1740
00:56:47,082 --> 00:56:48,082
(Like a friend's mom giving out snacks)

1741
00:56:48,083 --> 00:56:49,612
Whose mother is she?

1742
00:56:49,712 --> 00:56:51,052
We should cut it.

1743
00:56:51,782 --> 00:56:54,092
- What would you like? - Maybe a knife.

1744
00:56:54,392 --> 00:56:55,522
A knife?

1745
00:56:56,152 --> 00:56:57,822
You look so kind.

1746
00:56:58,622 --> 00:57:00,092
You look so kind, ma'am.

1747
00:57:00,592 --> 00:57:02,461
- Thank you. - Thank you.

1748
00:57:02,462 --> 00:57:03,732
Thank you for the food.

1749
00:57:03,792 --> 00:57:06,001
The warm box must have been rice cakes.

1750
00:57:06,002 --> 00:57:07,061
- Yes. - Right?

1751
00:57:07,062 --> 00:57:09,001
- Over there. - The one that was over there?

1752
00:57:09,002 --> 00:57:11,102
I had to take them out for you.

1753
00:57:11,402 --> 00:57:14,871
We talked about this before,

1754
00:57:14,872 --> 00:57:17,381
but you've been running a snack bar for 53 years in the same building?

1755
00:57:17,382 --> 00:57:19,781
For 54 years. I started in 1973.

1756
00:57:19,782 --> 00:57:21,281
So, it's a year younger than me.

1757
00:57:21,282 --> 00:57:22,412
- A year younger. - Really?

1758
00:57:23,052 --> 00:57:25,821
The Children's Grand Park opened in 1973.

1759
00:57:25,822 --> 00:57:27,492
- It did. - On May 5.

1760
00:57:27,592 --> 00:57:29,952
We weren't ready to open, so we opened on June 15.

1761
00:57:30,252 --> 00:57:31,261
I can forget everything,

1762
00:57:31,262 --> 00:57:33,122
but I can't forget those dates.

1763
00:57:33,722 --> 00:57:35,361
In the year the Children's Grand Park opened,

1764
00:57:35,362 --> 00:57:36,661
- Yes. - you also opened the bar.

1765
00:57:36,662 --> 00:57:37,701
(It's as old as the Children's Grand Park.)

1766
00:57:37,702 --> 00:57:40,971
Did you and your husband open it together?

1767
00:57:40,972 --> 00:57:43,771
Yes. At first, it was only this half.

1768
00:57:43,772 --> 00:57:45,401
- Okay. - I see.

1769
00:57:45,402 --> 00:57:46,601
- It was half. - This was a different shop.

1770
00:57:46,602 --> 00:57:48,341
It was half this size. We called it a mom-and-pop store.

1771
00:57:48,342 --> 00:57:49,871
- Now, they call it a grocery store. - Yes.

1772
00:57:49,872 --> 00:57:50,881
That was how we started.

1773
00:57:50,882 --> 00:57:52,512
- Was it a grocery store? - At first.

1774
00:57:52,642 --> 00:57:54,851
- That went on for about 12 years. - Okay.

1775
00:57:54,852 --> 00:57:56,551
And we sold a lot of jjolbokki here.

1776
00:57:56,552 --> 00:57:58,081
- I see. - Jjolbokki.

1777
00:57:58,082 --> 00:57:59,452
It was so tasty.

1778
00:57:59,682 --> 00:58:02,791
And then, we switched.

1779
00:58:02,792 --> 00:58:04,791
- It started out as a grocery store, - Yes.

1780
00:58:04,792 --> 00:58:07,092
- but you expanded and... - We sold jjolbokki here.

1781
00:58:07,362 --> 00:58:09,732
So, I was familiar with it.

1782
00:58:10,062 --> 00:58:11,402
It was so popular back then.

1783
00:58:11,432 --> 00:58:13,001
It was packed with girls.

1784
00:58:13,002 --> 00:58:14,748
(Her jjolbokki was sensational at the time.)

1785
00:58:14,772 --> 00:58:18,101
- Also, the Children's Grand Park... - Yes.

1786
00:58:18,102 --> 00:58:21,671
- It's got a good park. - At the time,

1787
00:58:21,672 --> 00:58:24,482
it was the best and biggest park in Seoul.

1788
00:58:24,612 --> 00:58:27,341
It was the best children's park in Seoul.

1789
00:58:27,342 --> 00:58:29,651
Your business must have done so well.

1790
00:58:29,652 --> 00:58:31,451
When they came for picnics,

1791
00:58:31,452 --> 00:58:34,091
there was an endless line of elementary school kids.

1792
00:58:34,092 --> 00:58:36,021
They'd even walk here from Haengdang-dong.

1793
00:58:36,022 --> 00:58:37,251
I often had picnics here as well.

1794
00:58:37,252 --> 00:58:38,261
- In elementary school. - Back in the day...

1795
00:58:38,262 --> 00:58:40,321
- Almost all kids came by. - Right.

1796
00:58:40,322 --> 00:58:42,291
- It was so popular. - It was.

1797
00:58:42,292 --> 00:58:44,232
They had 24 classes in 1 grade.

1798
00:58:45,732 --> 00:58:47,252
And there are like 50 kids in 1 class.

1799
00:58:47,302 --> 00:58:49,101
- I remember! - Gosh.

1800
00:58:49,102 --> 00:58:50,771
- Man. - Only one grade...

1801
00:58:50,772 --> 00:58:53,201
One school goes on a picnic,

1802
00:58:53,202 --> 00:58:55,942
and all the roads are packed with buses.

1803
00:58:55,972 --> 00:58:58,218
- The baby boomer generation... - There's a whole parade.

1804
00:58:58,242 --> 00:59:00,141
We also had 15 to 16 classes.

1805
00:59:00,142 --> 00:59:02,711
Right. These schools had 24 classes in a grade.

1806
00:59:02,712 --> 00:59:04,651
- Twenty-four classes? - It's an elementary school.

1807
00:59:04,652 --> 00:59:06,028
(There were far more students back then.)

1808
00:59:06,052 --> 00:59:08,252
Back in my day, we didn't have enough desks.

1809
00:59:08,552 --> 00:59:09,552
I'm not even joking.

1810
00:59:09,553 --> 00:59:11,393
Transfer students had to stand up for a while.

1811
00:59:12,792 --> 00:59:13,992
Because we ran out of desks.

1812
00:59:16,032 --> 00:59:17,361
- Come on. - I'm serious!

1813
00:59:17,362 --> 00:59:19,361
How can they run out of desks for transfer students?

1814
00:59:19,362 --> 00:59:21,232
- Come on now. - I'm serious!

1815
00:59:21,532 --> 00:59:23,001
- What... - What?

1816
00:59:23,002 --> 00:59:24,702
The school isn't a standing concert.

1817
00:59:25,102 --> 00:59:26,801
- How can they have class like this? - They were on their feet.

1818
00:59:26,802 --> 00:59:29,341
- Not even a chair? - He was told to stand there...

1819
00:59:29,342 --> 00:59:31,181
- until they brought a desk. - They went and got it.

1820
00:59:31,182 --> 00:59:32,182
He had to wait, standing up.

1821
00:59:32,183 --> 00:59:34,651
There were that many students.

1822
00:59:34,652 --> 00:59:36,311
- I was almost mistaken. - There were so many.

1823
00:59:36,312 --> 00:59:39,321
If you've been here for over 50 years,

1824
00:59:39,322 --> 00:59:41,021
it means you started in your 20s.

1825
00:59:41,022 --> 00:59:42,721
- Right. - You spent your entire youth here.

1826
00:59:42,722 --> 00:59:43,722
I did.

1827
00:59:43,722 --> 00:59:44,722
(She spent all of her youth here.)

1828
00:59:44,723 --> 00:59:46,561
- That's cool. - Until my hair turned grey.

1829
00:59:46,562 --> 00:59:47,831
- That's admirable. - That's admirable.

1830
00:59:47,832 --> 00:59:50,902
The building and the sign were the same,

1831
00:59:51,162 --> 00:59:53,632
but I wasn't sure if she'd still be here when I came.

1832
00:59:53,862 --> 00:59:55,072
I was so surprised.

1833
00:59:55,602 --> 00:59:57,101
- You've visited a few times. - I have.

1834
00:59:57,102 --> 00:59:58,271
You sat over there.

1835
00:59:58,272 --> 01:00:00,271
Yes, I usually sat there.

1836
01:00:00,272 --> 01:00:03,042
He's now a professor at Sejong University now.

1837
01:00:04,742 --> 01:00:06,611
- Is that true? - Yes.

1838
01:00:06,612 --> 01:00:08,212
I'll come back with my students one day.

1839
01:00:08,382 --> 01:00:09,751
He'll come back with his students.

1840
01:00:09,752 --> 01:00:11,881
- He'll throw a party. - I'll pay for everything.

1841
01:00:11,882 --> 01:00:13,852
He might even give his lecture here.

1842
01:00:14,022 --> 01:00:15,522
I can't do that.

1843
01:00:15,892 --> 01:00:17,821
- You have to pay, Professor Ahn. - Of course.

1844
01:00:17,822 --> 01:00:19,662
You should make a short film here.

1845
01:00:20,692 --> 01:00:22,561
Running your shop here,

1846
01:00:22,562 --> 01:00:24,631
there must have been many rewarding moments.

1847
01:00:24,632 --> 01:00:26,361
Right. I had arranged a lot of marriages.

1848
01:00:26,362 --> 01:00:27,731
- You were a matchmaker? - Seriously?

1849
01:00:27,732 --> 01:00:29,072
- Yes. - Between students?

1850
01:00:29,132 --> 01:00:30,172
Between students.

1851
01:00:30,672 --> 01:00:32,601
- You were the matchmaker? - They're a college couple, then.

1852
01:00:32,602 --> 01:00:34,941
No, not me. My husband did it.

1853
01:00:34,942 --> 01:00:38,082
This male student was going to Hanyang University,

1854
01:00:38,342 --> 01:00:40,082
and he was set up with a dance major here.

1855
01:00:40,182 --> 01:00:41,811
He fell in love and came here every day.

1856
01:00:41,812 --> 01:00:42,812
(He used to come here all the time.)

1857
01:00:42,813 --> 01:00:45,451
Asking us to set them up.

1858
01:00:45,452 --> 01:00:48,151
So, we brought them to a hotel, and I left.

1859
01:00:48,152 --> 01:00:50,822
- Really? - Now, they're happily married.

1860
01:00:51,792 --> 01:00:53,362
- That's so wholesome. - Yes.

1861
01:00:53,722 --> 01:00:56,231
What made you apply for this show?

1862
01:00:56,232 --> 01:00:57,331
The show?

1863
01:00:57,332 --> 01:00:59,208
I've been running this shop for a long time now.

1864
01:00:59,232 --> 01:01:02,002
I can't predict how long I'll be here.

1865
01:01:02,602 --> 01:01:03,731
I'm getting old now,

1866
01:01:03,732 --> 01:01:05,671
and I really enjoyed the show...

1867
01:01:05,672 --> 01:01:07,202
and thought you were such nice people.

1868
01:01:07,612 --> 01:01:09,911
- The games looked so fun too. - Right.

1869
01:01:09,912 --> 01:01:12,311
You put water on your spoons,

1870
01:01:12,312 --> 01:01:14,042
and dropped water 1 by 1.

1871
01:01:14,452 --> 01:01:15,881
When Eun I was here.

1872
01:01:15,882 --> 01:01:16,911
(The game that made Jae Suk pay)

1873
01:01:16,912 --> 01:01:18,981
The games are so entertaining.

1874
01:01:18,982 --> 01:01:21,522
You're great at games.

1875
01:01:21,792 --> 01:01:22,792
I...

1876
01:01:23,852 --> 01:01:25,861
I'm better than him.

1877
01:01:25,862 --> 01:01:27,522
- Yes. - Overall, I mean.

1878
01:01:27,862 --> 01:01:29,331
I was doing pretty well at first.

1879
01:01:29,332 --> 01:01:31,031
I'm experiencing a slump recently.

1880
01:01:31,032 --> 01:01:32,231
And in the baseball game,

1881
01:01:32,232 --> 01:01:33,362
you hit it way too hard.

1882
01:01:34,532 --> 01:01:35,571
You really watch our show.

1883
01:01:35,572 --> 01:01:37,742
I guess you never watched the games I did well in.

1884
01:01:38,602 --> 01:01:39,971
- He does well in practice. - He does.

1885
01:01:39,972 --> 01:01:41,712
I get nervous in the actual games.

1886
01:01:41,812 --> 01:01:44,012
I should show her today.

1887
01:01:45,782 --> 01:01:47,342
- Should we... - Yes.

1888
01:01:47,482 --> 01:01:49,182
I have the ones he advertises.

1889
01:01:51,082 --> 01:01:53,481
She bought the ones that you advertise.

1890
01:01:53,482 --> 01:01:54,891
- Which one? - The drinks.

1891
01:01:54,892 --> 01:01:55,952
Goodness.

1892
01:01:58,022 --> 01:01:59,822
All of a sudden...

1893
01:02:00,262 --> 01:02:01,831
- I had them prepared. - This is so out of the blue.

1894
01:02:01,832 --> 01:02:03,892
- Jae Suk advertises it. - Right.

1895
01:02:03,992 --> 01:02:06,562
My contract is renewed, thanks to you.

1896
01:02:06,932 --> 01:02:08,001
Thank you.

1897
01:02:08,002 --> 01:02:09,271
- The vitamin drink, right? - Yes.

1898
01:02:09,272 --> 01:02:11,542
I've been working with them for a long time now.

1899
01:02:13,142 --> 01:02:14,172
Let's cheer up.

1900
01:02:14,372 --> 01:02:15,442
Gosh.

1901
01:02:15,512 --> 01:02:16,911
The higher the number, the better.

1902
01:02:16,912 --> 01:02:18,611
Let's throw it on the floor.

1903
01:02:18,612 --> 01:02:19,642
- On the floor? - Yes.

1904
01:02:20,282 --> 01:02:22,312
- Can't you do it? - No.

1905
01:02:22,952 --> 01:02:24,781
You get to participate...

1906
01:02:24,782 --> 01:02:26,582
as many times as this number.

1907
01:02:26,982 --> 01:02:28,192
- I'll go. - Okay.

1908
01:02:31,062 --> 01:02:32,091
At least one.

1909
01:02:32,092 --> 01:02:33,792
(Their goal is 2.)

1910
01:02:33,822 --> 01:02:34,892
- One! - Yes!

1911
01:02:35,332 --> 01:02:37,132
- Once. - You can participate once.

1912
01:02:37,662 --> 01:02:38,662
- Perfect. - Yes.

1913
01:02:38,962 --> 01:02:41,472
Let's check out the prize for Round One.

1914
01:02:41,932 --> 01:02:43,302
I have bad sight, so...

1915
01:02:44,032 --> 01:02:45,272
I'll read it out for you.

1916
01:02:46,872 --> 01:02:49,642
"My rice cooker is 15 years old now."

1917
01:02:49,742 --> 01:02:53,041
"I'd like to cook glossy rice for the students."

1918
01:02:53,042 --> 01:02:55,651
"A 35-serving electric rice cooker."

1919
01:02:55,652 --> 01:02:57,052
- What? - Thirty-five servings?

1920
01:02:57,352 --> 01:02:59,122
- Thirty-five? - It must be gigantic.

1921
01:03:00,022 --> 01:03:01,851
- But you need that at restaurants. - Let me see.

1922
01:03:01,852 --> 01:03:02,852
That's...

1923
01:03:03,592 --> 01:03:05,022
This is brand new.

1924
01:03:07,062 --> 01:03:08,431
- Still... - Round One...

1925
01:03:08,432 --> 01:03:09,462
Play well.

1926
01:03:11,262 --> 01:03:12,301
The pressure.

1927
01:03:12,302 --> 01:03:13,502
(The pressure knocks him out.)

1928
01:03:13,902 --> 01:03:15,702
(Also feeling the pressure)

1929
01:03:15,932 --> 01:03:16,932
I want it.

1930
01:03:17,672 --> 01:03:19,371
(He's about to cry.)

1931
01:03:19,372 --> 01:03:20,802
(The mission for the rice cooker)

1932
01:03:20,842 --> 01:03:22,711
(A Close Call, Pot Lid)

1933
01:03:22,712 --> 01:03:23,971
(Bounce ping pong balls, )

1934
01:03:23,972 --> 01:03:27,141
(and put 2 of them on a pot lid.)

1935
01:03:27,142 --> 01:03:29,352
(But you only get 20 seconds.)

1936
01:03:29,552 --> 01:03:31,951
It might bounce off.

1937
01:03:31,952 --> 01:03:33,022
Right.

1938
01:03:33,352 --> 01:03:34,921
- Like this. - How do we do this?

1939
01:03:34,922 --> 01:03:36,802
(You want us to put them on the lid like this?)

1940
01:03:37,352 --> 01:03:39,191
- How do we do it? - It just has to bounce once?

1941
01:03:39,192 --> 01:03:40,222
At least once.

1942
01:03:40,792 --> 01:03:42,791
But we can't wait for it to stop...

1943
01:03:42,792 --> 01:03:44,312
- since there's a time limit. - Right.

1944
01:03:45,662 --> 01:03:46,702
This is...

1945
01:03:47,302 --> 01:03:48,771
It slanted that way,

1946
01:03:48,772 --> 01:03:50,701
so it always goes over.

1947
01:03:50,702 --> 01:03:53,002
I don't think you know what "moderate" means.

1948
01:03:53,142 --> 01:03:54,741
This is definitely going over.

1949
01:03:54,742 --> 01:03:55,742
Hey.

1950
01:03:56,642 --> 01:03:58,282
Why are they so difficult?

1951
01:03:58,682 --> 01:04:00,881
It always goes over.

1952
01:04:00,882 --> 01:04:02,251
(They keep failing during practice.)

1953
01:04:02,252 --> 01:04:03,851
- I can't do it. - Then...

1954
01:04:03,852 --> 01:04:05,682
- This is... - This one's hard.

1955
01:04:10,422 --> 01:04:12,962
How did you come up with this bizarre game?

1956
01:04:13,392 --> 01:04:14,961
(He spoke his mind out of the blue.)

1957
01:04:14,962 --> 01:04:15,992
But I did it earlier.

1958
01:04:16,862 --> 01:04:18,501
(One person is silently practicing.)

1959
01:04:18,502 --> 01:04:19,562
To the back.

1960
01:04:19,962 --> 01:04:21,002
Use your thumb.

1961
01:04:21,332 --> 01:04:22,678
- Do you get what I mean? - No, your index finger.

1962
01:04:22,702 --> 01:04:24,302
(Concentrating)

1963
01:04:24,802 --> 01:04:26,971
See? It's slanted.

1964
01:04:26,972 --> 01:04:28,472
(Close)

1965
01:04:29,372 --> 01:04:31,072
- Yes! - Good.

1966
01:04:31,182 --> 01:04:32,442
Kyung Nam, you're...

1967
01:04:32,642 --> 01:04:33,802
- Hey. - How did you do that?

1968
01:04:34,142 --> 01:04:36,682
- It's not that difficult. - It's going that way.

1969
01:04:37,252 --> 01:04:38,582
It's really hard.

1970
01:04:40,752 --> 01:04:42,652
Like this? That's one on the lid, right?

1971
01:04:43,852 --> 01:04:45,521
(Kyung Nam is always the ace player.)

1972
01:04:45,522 --> 01:04:47,422
- Let's give it a try. - Okay.

1973
01:04:47,622 --> 01:04:49,542
- All right. - Let's do a chant together, ma'am.

1974
01:04:49,792 --> 01:04:50,962
- In 1, 2, 3. - In 1, 2, 3.

1975
01:04:51,032 --> 01:04:52,032
- Let's go! - Let's go!

1976
01:04:52,262 --> 01:04:54,031
- Which way should we go? - In 1, 2, 3.

1977
01:04:54,032 --> 01:04:55,392
- Here we go. - Who's going first?

1978
01:04:55,432 --> 01:04:56,531
- Should I go first? - Yes.

1979
01:04:56,532 --> 01:04:57,701
- Let's go this way. - Okay.

1980
01:04:57,702 --> 01:04:58,742
In this order.

1981
01:04:58,772 --> 01:05:00,242
- You get 20 seconds. Ready. - Okay.

1982
01:05:00,972 --> 01:05:01,972
Set.

1983
01:05:04,172 --> 01:05:05,741
(1st try)

1984
01:05:05,742 --> 01:05:06,782
No.

1985
01:05:07,982 --> 01:05:08,982
You did it.

1986
01:05:11,922 --> 01:05:12,952
Man.

1987
01:05:16,992 --> 01:05:19,122
(Don't fall!)

1988
01:05:24,162 --> 01:05:25,601
- That's it, Kyung Nam! - Yes.

1989
01:05:25,602 --> 01:05:26,631
(They put 1 on the lid.)

1990
01:05:26,632 --> 01:05:27,632
- Hurry. - Ten seconds.

1991
01:05:28,072 --> 01:05:29,671
- We've got time. - We have time.

1992
01:05:29,672 --> 01:05:31,272
This part is raised. Put one here.

1993
01:05:31,742 --> 01:05:33,272
Slowly.

1994
01:05:33,902 --> 01:05:35,972
- All right. - Five, four,

1995
01:05:38,082 --> 01:05:39,141
three...

1996
01:05:39,142 --> 01:05:41,142
(First try failed.)

1997
01:05:41,912 --> 01:05:43,912
The sound of the whistle is very discouraging.

1998
01:05:46,252 --> 01:05:47,351
Gosh.

1999
01:05:47,352 --> 01:05:49,291
(First try ended, and they're discouraged.)

2000
01:05:49,292 --> 01:05:50,622
This is too...

2001
01:05:51,662 --> 01:05:53,421
(Peeking)

2002
01:05:53,422 --> 01:05:56,132
Guys, look at her eyes once.

2003
01:05:56,462 --> 01:05:57,491
Let's get a grip.

2004
01:05:57,492 --> 01:05:58,532
(We should get a grip.)

2005
01:05:58,662 --> 01:05:59,662
Let's get a grip.

2006
01:05:59,663 --> 01:06:00,802
(Glancing)

2007
01:06:01,272 --> 01:06:03,071
(Bracing herself)

2008
01:06:03,072 --> 01:06:04,231
Kyung Nam is doing...

2009
01:06:04,232 --> 01:06:05,472
I'm pretty good.

2010
01:06:05,872 --> 01:06:06,872
How did you do it?

2011
01:06:07,002 --> 01:06:08,011
You have to do it gently.

2012
01:06:08,012 --> 01:06:09,512
- You got it. - Also, I think...

2013
01:06:10,542 --> 01:06:11,582
No, we got it.

2014
01:06:11,882 --> 01:06:13,042
We're going to pass this one.

2015
01:06:13,342 --> 01:06:14,511
- Should we start? - Can I go first?

2016
01:06:14,512 --> 01:06:15,552
- Okay. - In that order.

2017
01:06:15,812 --> 01:06:16,812
In 1, 2, 3.

2018
01:06:16,813 --> 01:06:18,021
- Here we go! - Here we go!

2019
01:06:18,022 --> 01:06:19,022
Try number two.

2020
01:06:19,023 --> 01:06:21,021
(Out of 10 total tries, they're on try number 2.)

2021
01:06:21,022 --> 01:06:22,291
(We will...)

2022
01:06:22,292 --> 01:06:23,752
(succeed this time!)

2023
01:06:24,052 --> 01:06:25,092
Set.

2024
01:06:25,722 --> 01:06:28,031
(2nd try)

2025
01:06:28,032 --> 01:06:29,032
- Yes. - I think you got it.

2026
01:06:29,033 --> 01:06:30,092
- No! - Kyung Nam.

2027
01:06:31,462 --> 01:06:32,561
- Nice, Kyung Nam. - Great.

2028
01:06:32,562 --> 01:06:34,031
- He's so good. - He did it.

2029
01:06:34,032 --> 01:06:35,072
(They put 1 on the lid.)

2030
01:06:35,632 --> 01:06:38,272
(One more, and they succeed.)

2031
01:06:39,542 --> 01:06:40,572
I think she got it.

2032
01:06:41,512 --> 01:06:42,512
(I think she got it.)

2033
01:06:42,513 --> 01:06:43,542
Yes!

2034
01:06:44,242 --> 01:06:45,441
I think she got it.

2035
01:06:45,442 --> 01:06:46,442
(A ball fell off.)

2036
01:06:46,443 --> 01:06:47,881
- Ten seconds remaining! - They have to stay on it.

2037
01:06:47,882 --> 01:06:48,882
Good.

2038
01:06:49,082 --> 01:06:50,281
- Gentle. - Jae Suk.

2039
01:06:50,282 --> 01:06:52,351
- Five, four, - Do it.

2040
01:06:52,352 --> 01:06:53,721
Three, two...

2041
01:06:53,722 --> 01:06:54,992
- He's got it. - Yes!

2042
01:06:55,692 --> 01:06:57,521
- Three, two... - He's got it.

2043
01:06:57,522 --> 01:06:58,921
(Jae Suk finished it with 2 seconds left!)

2044
01:06:58,922 --> 01:07:00,621
- We did it! - It came to a stop.

2045
01:07:00,622 --> 01:07:01,632
Yes!

2046
01:07:02,532 --> 01:07:03,592
We did it!

2047
01:07:04,332 --> 01:07:06,131
- It came to a stop. - You did it.

2048
01:07:06,132 --> 01:07:07,161
No way.

2049
01:07:07,162 --> 01:07:09,031
(A big smile)

2050
01:07:09,032 --> 01:07:10,371
We did it.

2051
01:07:10,372 --> 01:07:11,441
(Who called me Practice World Messi?)

